Doc,<br><br>
you said:<br><br>
&quot;I wonder how many Post Office employee's have it &lt;g&gt; ?&quot;<br><br>
Actually, quite a few (I know some), along with fire and police departments, emt's, healthcare and counseling professionals, safety (that's me), hospital workers, etc.<br><br>
You get the picture. It fits an interesting pattern. Certain kinds of work fit into the puzzle and allow the expression of PTSD in a socially acceptable and constructive manner. We are just COMPULSIVE about EVERYTHING! It doesn't control it, just lets it out on a leash. It also delays the collapse of things in some people, as it did me. It bought me time, but I couln't out run it in the end!<br><br>
'Nam Vets are not the only people with PTSD. Physically and sexually abused children are right in there too, along with rape victims, and the victims of other violent crime, airplane crash survivors, and so on.<br><br>
There really needs to be more public education and understanding, don't you think? 
